repo.description: The most widely used Python to C compiler
repo.name: cython

body:
Continuing to Pythonize Ð¡ython documentation!

This PR Pythonizes [this](https://cython.readthedocs.io/en/latest/src/tutorial/cdef_classes.html) documentation page.

Lots of process details and standardization are found here: #4187 

BTW, the fact that this is a draft PR does not mean that you can no longer leave review, as I understand it, so I urge you to do it.

comment_data.body:
There's a few of these big chunks where the only thing is changed is the indentation.

Is there good reason for this change? If there isn't then I think leave the indentation as it was (it makes it harder to spot other changes)
comment_data.diff_hunk:
@@ -43,25 +63,35 @@ little calling overhead compared to a cdef method.
 
 To make the class definitions visible to other modules, and thus allow for
 efficient C-level usage and inheritance outside of the module that
-implements them, we define them in a :file:`sin_of_square.pxd` file:
+implements them, we define them in:
 
 .. literalinclude:: ../../examples/tutorial/cdef_classes/sin_of_square.pxd
+    :caption: sin_of_square.pxd
 
 Using this, we can now change our integration example:
 
-.. literalinclude:: ../../examples/tutorial/cdef_classes/integrate.pyx
+.. tabs::
+    .. group-tab:: Pure Python
+
+        .. literalinclude:: ../../examples/tutorial/cdef_classes/integrate.py
+            :caption: integrate.py
+
+    .. group-tab:: Cython
+
+        .. literalinclude:: ../../examples/tutorial/cdef_classes/integrate.pyx
+             :caption: integrate.pyx
 
 This is almost as fast as the previous code, however it is much more flexible
 as the function to integrate can be changed. We can even pass in a new
 function defined in Python-space::
 
-  >>> import integrate
-  >>> class MyPolynomial(integrate.Function):
-  ...     def evaluate(self, x):
-  ...         return 2*x*x + 3*x - 10
-  ...
-  >>> integrate(MyPolynomial(), 0, 1, 10000)
-  -7.8335833300000077
+    >>> import integrate
+    >>> class MyPolynomial(integrate.Function):
+    ...     def evaluate(self, x):
+    ...         return 2*x*x + 3*x - 10
+    ...
+    >>> integrate(MyPolynomial(), 0, 1, 10000)
+    -7.8335833300000077

comment_data.body:
A good reason to add indentation is to keep it the same throughout the documentation.

It's just that it's not very convenient for me if in one `rst` indentation - 4 spaces, in the other - 2

comment_data.body: @da-woods yes, I agree that because of this it is more difficult to see the real changes, so I can make a separate PR that would fix the indentation for all `rst` documents.

commit.message: tutorial\cdef_classes.rst: format: 4 spaces for indentation, ** for title
tutorial\cdef_classes.rst: return `literalinclude` and add it to tabs
cdef_classes\math_function_2.pyx: add blank lines for alignment
math_function_2.py: use cython.locals to match the cython version
math_function_2.pyx: add blank lines for alignment
math_function_2.pyx: remove blank lines for alignment
sin_of_square.pyx: add blank lines for alignment
integrate.pyx: add blank lines for alignment
two-syntax-variants-used: add content to note, content does not change
math_function_2.pyx & sin_of_square.pyx: remove blank lines for alignment
integrate.pyx: remove blank lines for alignment
wave_function.pyx: add blank lines for alignment
nonecheck.pyx: add blank lines for alignment
